<p><strong>Procedure for submission, review and selection of essays and research papers:</strong><br>There are two procedures for sending, academic peer review and selection of essays and research papers for the purpose of its publication in the ANIDIP: (i) research trials submitted to the&nbsp;Blattmann, Odio Benito and Steiner&nbsp;essay contest. (Ii) Research presented doctoral candidates, academics and professional career.</p>
<p><br><strong>PUBLIC CALL FOR RESEARCH ARTICLES</strong><br>&nbsp;After receiving the research will proceed to give them anonymity by assigning a number and send it to anonymous peers of recognized competence in international criminal law for evaluation within one month after receipt, which will continue the following criteria:<br>&nbsp;<br>- Thesis: (i) conceptual value of the thesis defended at the trial; (Ii) clarity on the approach; (Iii) innovative. - Argument: (i) conceptual value of the arguments presented in support of the thesis; (Ii) depth development of the arguments; (Iii) the innovative nature of the arguments (beyond analyzing the arguments presented by other authors); (Iv) logical link between the defended thesis and the arguments in support of it.<br>&nbsp;- Sources: (i) quotation of the most important matter for international and national doctrinal sources; (Ii) variety of legislative and legal sources of international (and national character when relevant to the test object).<br>&nbsp;- Form: respect for the rules contained in Annex I of the Convocation of Competition (in the maximum length of trials, as in the format and rules of citation).<br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;In their evaluations anonymous peers determine the acceptance or rejection for publication of the papers and collect recommendations for improvement of those who were accepted.<br>The anonymous peers evaluations will be sent to the authors of the respective tests in order to review them, within a period of thirty days.<br>&nbsp;<br>The amount of research to be published in each issue will depend on the quality and anonymous peers assessments.<br>&nbsp;<br><strong><strong>BLATTMANN, ODIO BENITO AND STEINER&nbsp;</strong>ESSAY CONTEST EDITION ON INTERNATIONAL CRIMINAL JUSTICE</strong><br>&nbsp;Once the deadline (April 5, 2015) is finished, the tests will be classified by the nationality of their authors. In the event that the number of tests from nationals of the same State does not exceed five, it may be included in the same category tests to the nationals of two or more States. This classification shall be made to provide anonymity to the tests by assigning a number.<br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;The trials of each national category will be sent anonymously to a national jury of different nationalities (ie, the national jury of Chile will send the essays submitted by nationals of Colombia, and Argentina will be sent to the tests presented by nationals of Peru , to give, not real) hypothetical examples. National juries will have until May 5, 2015 to select the best essay of received; the members of each of the national juries are given in Annex II to this Call.<br>&nbsp;<br>The June 5, 2015, an international jury composed of the following three members shall be established:<br>&nbsp;<br>(I) Elizabeth Odio Benito, former Judge of the International Criminal Court (2003- 2012).<br>(Ii) Hector Olásolo, President of the Ibero-American Institute in The Hague (2011- 2015); Career and Professor at the University of Rosario.<br>(Iii) A representative of the Ibero-American General Secretariat.<br>&nbsp;<br>The international jury will evaluate anonymously all selected by national juries way trials and determine the June 5, 2015 the winning essay of the fourth edition of the competition. Likewise, the international jury will mark those other trials, with appropriate modifications, could have the quality required for publication in the ANIDIP.<br>&nbsp;<br>Each national jury when selecting the test to be sent to the international jury will report on it in which recommendations for improvement regarding their possible publication are collected. The international jury present, also, a report with recommendations for each of the tests considers that they could be published.<br>&nbsp;<br>Reports from national and international judges will be sent to the authors of the respective tests to the effect that, as far as possible and within a maximum period of 30 days, enter the comments in them.<br>&nbsp;<br>New versions of each of the trials pre-selected for publication will be subject to a new anonymous evaluation during the month of July 2015 by two members of the Editorial Board and / or Scientific Ibero-American Yearbook of International Criminal Law. Only when the result of this re-evaluation is positive we will proceed to the publication of the pre-selected tests that have not been winners of the fourth edition of the Essay Contest. The new amendments proposed by the respective assessors will be sent to the authors of the respective tests to the effect that, as far as possible and within a maximum period of 15 days, introduce them. Likewise, the authors updated their trials at this time.<br>&nbsp;<br>The final version of the tests that will be published will be received no later than September 1, 2015, to the effect that the Publishing House of the Universidad del Rosario to develop the process of layout and editing so that Volume III the ANIDIP appear in the first quarter of 2015.<br>For more information see in this respect the "Announcements" section.</p>
